  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several important ways:\n\n1. International Conventions and Standards\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- These provide framework for national anti-money laundering (AML) legislation\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries cooperate in investigating and prosecuting money laundering\n- Extradition treaties\n- Information sharing between financial intelligence units\n- Cross-border legal cooperation mechanisms\n\n3. Compliance Requirements\n- Banks and financial institutions must implement international AML standards\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- Customer due diligence procedures\n\n4. Regulatory Harmonization\n- Countries align national laws with international standards\n- Consistent definitions of money laundering\n- Similar criminalization approaches\n- Comparable enforcement mechanisms\n\n5. Sanctions and Enforcement\n- International sanctions against non-compliant jurisdictions\n- Potential economic penalties\n- Diplomatic pressure to improve AML frameworks\n\n6. Technological Challenges\n- Emerging technologies like cryptocurrencies\n- Need for coordinated international regulatory responses\n- Developing consistent approaches to digital financial crime\n\nThese intersections create a complex but interconnected global approach to combating money laundering.",
